Jean Renoir |work=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=2 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite journal |date=December 1959 |title=Notre couverture |trans-title=Our cover |journal=[[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]] |language=French |issue=102 |ref=CITEREFCahiers du cin\u00e9ma, December 1959 }}\n\n: {{cite journal |date=February 1960 |title=Les dix meilleurs films de l'ann\u00e9e |trans-title=The ten best films of the year |journal=Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma |language=French |issue=104 |ref=CITEREFCahiers du cin\u00e9ma, February 1960 }}\n\n: {{cite web |author=[[Cin\u00e9-Ressources]] |url=http://cinema.encyclopedie.films.bifi.fr/index.php?pk=50831 |title=Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe |language=French |publisher=[[Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que Fran\u00e7aise]] |accessdate=26 February 2020 |ref=CITEREFCin\u00e9-Ressources }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Douchet |first=Jean |authorlink=Jean Douchet |year=1974 |chapter=Le Dejeuner sur l'Herbe (1959) (Picnic on the Grass, 1960) |editor-last=Truffaut |editor-first=Fran\u00e7ois |editorlink=Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut |translator1-last=Halsey II |translator1-first=W. W. |translator2-last=Simon |translator2-first=William H. |title=Jean Renoir by Andr\u00e9 Bazin |location=London and New York |publisher=W. H. Allen |pp=294-300 |isbn=0-491-01412-0 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Durgnat |first=Raymond |authorlink=Raymond Durgnat |year=1974 |title=Jean Renoir |location=Berkeley and Los Angeles |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=0-520-02283-1 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Faulkner |first=Christopher |year=1979 |title=Jean Renoir, a guide to references and resources |location=Boston |publisher=G. K. Hall |isbn=0-8161-7912-3 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |last=French |first=Philip |authorlink=Philip French |date=8 July 2007 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2007/jul/08/featuresreview.review6 |title=Other DVDs: Jean Renoir Boxset |work=[[The Observer]] |accessdate=29 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Frey |first=Hugo |year=2014 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U6H8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA119 |title=Nationalism and the Cinema in France: Political Mythologies and Film Events, 1945\u20131995 |location=New York and Oxford |publisher=Berghahn Books |isbn=978-1-78238-365-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last=Hillier |editor-first=Jim |year=1985 |chapter=Appendix 1: ''Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma'' Annual Best Film Listings 1955\u20139 |title=Cahiers du Cinema: The 1950s: Neo-Realism, Hollywood, New Wave |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=0-674-09060-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Hischak |first=Thomas S. |year=2015 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xz99CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA412 |title=The Encyclopedia of Film Composers |location=Lanham, Maryland |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1-4422-4549-5 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite news |last=Lachize |first=Samuel |date=14 November 1959 |title=''Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe'': fallait-il tenter l'exp\u00e9rience? |trans-title=''Picnic on the Grass'': should the experience be tried? |work=[[L'Humanit\u00e9]] |language=French |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Marie |first=Laurent |year=2013 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FxkI2SycFHwC&pg=PA328 |chapter=Renoir and the French Communist Party: The Grand Disillusion |editor1-last=Phillips |editor1-first=Alastair |editor2-last=Vincendeau |editor2-first=Ginette |editor2-link=Ginette Vincendeau |title=A Companion to Jean Renoir |location=Oxford |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |pp=328\u2013346 |isbn=978-1-4443-3853-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=M\u00e9rigeau |first=Pascal |authorlink=Pascal M\u00e9rigeau |year=2017 |orig-year=2012 |title=Jean Renoir: A Biography |translator-last=Benderson |translator-first=Bruce |location=Burbank, California |publisher=Ratpac Press and Running Press |isbn=978-0-7624-5596-6 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Nichols |first=Mary P. |year=2000 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FpEAaYF0jqEC&pg=PA95 |title=Reconstructing Woody: Art, Love, and Life in the Films of Woody Allen |location=Lanham, Maryland |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=0-8476-8989-1 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |last=Oddos |first=Val\u00e9rie |date=6 December 2016 |url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/culture/arts-expos/peinture/cagnes-sur-mer-au-milieu-des-oliviers-le-musee-renoir-a-rouvert-ses-portes_3382189.html |title=Cagnes-sur-Mer : au milieu des oliviers, le mus\u00e9e Renoir a rouvert ses portes |trans-title=Cagnes-sur-Mer: in the middle of olive trees, the Renoir museum has reopened its doors |work=[[France Info (TV channel)|France Info]] |language=French |accessdate=20 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last1=Phillips |editor1-first=Alastair |editor-last2=Vincendeau |editor2-first=Ginette |year=2013 |chapter=Filmography |title=A Companion to Jean Renoir |location=Oxford |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |pp=572\u2013584 |isbn=978-1-4443-3853-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Renoir |first=Jean |year=1974 |title=My Life and My Films |translator-last=Denny |translator-first=Norman |location=New York |publisher=Da Capo Press |isbn=0-306-80457-3 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Renoir |first=Jean |year=1989 |title=Renoir on Renoir: Interviews, Essays, and Remarks |translator-last=Volk |translator-first=Carol |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-38593-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Rohmer |first=\u00c9ric |authorlink=\u00c9ric Rohmer |date=December 1959 |title=Jeunesse de Jean Renoir |trans-title=Jean Renoir's youth |journal=Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma |language=French |issue=102 |pp=1\u20137 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last=Rivi\u00e8re |editor-first=Marie-Sylvie |year=2018 |chapter-url=https://services.jamesnook.com/services/storage?type=document&id=225222&secret=PDEc67rdlHn3SI3XwAYQIplX2qRvfq61spuq6eE4 |chapter=Go\u00fbter l'Europe |trans-chapter=Taste Europe |title=Quelle Europe voulons-nous ? En suppl\u00e9ment: une s\u00e9lection d'articles et d'entretiens |trans-title=What Europe do we want? Supplement: a selection of articles and interviews |language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Semaines sociales de France |pp=45\u201357 |isbn=9782322102792 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Silke |first=James R. |year=2005 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vmMH_muqTycC&pg=PA134 |chapter=Jean Renoir on Love, Hollywood, Authors, and Critics |editor-last=Cardullo |editor-first=Bert |title=Jean Renoir: Interviews |location=Jackson, Mississippi |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |isbn=1-57806-730-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |author=''Time Out'' |authorlink=Time Out (magazine) |url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/le-dejeuner-sur-lherbe |title=Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'Herbe |accessdate=2 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0052765}}\n* {{Amg movie|38085|Picnic on the Grass}}\n\n{{Jean Renoir}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Picnic On The Grass}}\n[[Category:1959 films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jean Renoir]]\n[[Category:1950s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1950s satirical films]]\n[[Category:Artificial insemination]]\n[[Category:French romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:French satirical films]]\n[[Category:Films based on Greco-Roman mythology]]\n[[Category:Eugenics in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n", "name_user": "Ffranc", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picnic_on_the_Grass"}
{"title_page": "Kazutomo Iguchi", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese baseball player}}\n{{Infobox NPB player\n|name=Kazutomo Iguchi\n|image=\n|image_size=250px\n|caption=\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|team=Hokkaido Nippon Ham Fighters\n|number=29\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1994|1|7}}\n|birth_place=Yokohama, Kanagawa, Japan\n|debutdate=March 30\n|debutyear=2016\n|debutteam=[[Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters]]\n| statyear      = 2016 season\n| statleague    = NPB\n| stat1label    = [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013Loss]]\n| stat1value    = 0-1\n| stat2label    = [[Save (baseball)|Save]]s\n| stat2value    = 0\n| stat3label    = [[Earned run average|ERA]]\n| stat3value    = 3.86\n| stat4label    = [[Strikeout]]s\n| stat4value    = 27|teams=\n* [[Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters]] ({{npby|2016}}\u2013present)\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Kazutomo Iguchi'''|\u4e95\u53e3 \u548c\u670b|Iguchi Kazutomo|extra=born January 7, 1994 in [[Yokohama]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture|Kanagawa]], Japan}} is a professional Japanese [[baseball]] player. He plays [[pitcher]] for the [[Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters]].\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|brm=iguchi000kaz}}\n* [http://npb.jp/bis/eng/players/31335132.html NPB.com]\n\n{{Hokkaido Nippon Ham Fighters roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iguchi, Kazutomo}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Baseball people from Yokohama]]\n[[Category:Japanese baseball players]]\n[[Category:Nippon Professional Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters players]]\n\n\n{{Japan-baseball-pitcher-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NPB player\n|name=Kazutomo Iguchi\n|image=\n|image_size=250px\n|caption=\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|team=Hokkaido Nippon Ham Fighters\n|number=29\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1994|1|7}}\n|birth_place=Yokohama, Kanagawa, Japan\n|debutdate=March 30\n|debutyear=2016\n|debutteam=[[Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters]]\n| statyear      = 2016 season\n| statleague    = NPB\n| stat1label    = [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013Loss]]\n| stat1value    = 0-1\n| stat2label    = [[Save (baseball)|Save]]s\n| stat2value    = 0\n| stat3label    = [[Earned run average|ERA]]\n| stat3value    = 3.86\n| stat4label    = [[Strikeout]]s\n| stat4value    = 27|teams=\n* [[Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters]] ({{npby|2016}}\u2013present)\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Kazutomo Iguchi'''|\u4e95\u53e3 \u548c\u670b|Iguchi Kazutomo|extra=born January 7, 1994 in [[Yokohama]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture|Kanagawa]], Japan}} is a professional Japanese [[baseball]] player. He plays [[pitcher]] for the [[Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters]].\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|brm=iguchi000kaz}}\n* [http://npb.jp/bis/eng/players/31335132.html NPB.com]\n\n{{Hokkaido Nippon Ham Fighters roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iguchi, Kazutomo}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Baseball people from Yokohama]]\n[[Category:Japanese baseball players]]\n[[Category:Nippon Professional Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters players]]\n\n\n{{Japan-baseball-pitcher-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Japanese baseball player\", overriding Wikidata description \"baseball player (1994-)\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazutomo_Iguchi"}
{"title_page": "Statue of Abraham Lincoln (Philadelphia)", "text_new": "{{Infobox monument\n| name          = Lincoln Monument\n| native_name   = \n| image         = Lincoln 1871 Fairmount.jpg\n| caption       = ''Lincoln the Emancipator''<ref name=\"Colimore\">Edward Colimore, ''The Philadelphia Inquirer's Guide to Historic Philadelphia'', (University Park, PA: Pennsylvania State University Press, 2003), p. 205.</ref>\n| location      = Kelly Drive & Sedgley Drive,<br>[[Fairmount Park]], Philadelphia\n| designer      = [[Randolph Rogers]]\n| type          = \n| material      = Sculpture: bronze<br>Base: granite & bronze\n| length        = \n| width         = \n| height        = Overall: {{cvt|26.5|ft|m|sortable=on}}<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/><br>Sculpture: {{cvt|8.67|ft|m|sortable=on}}\n| begin         = Commissioned 1866<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/><br>Cast 1870<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/>\n| complete      = \n| dedicated     =September 22, 1871<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/>\n| open          = \n| restore       = \n| dismantled    = \n| dedicated_to  = \n| map_name      = \n| map_text      = \n| map_width     = \n| map_relief    = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|39|58|10.56|N|75|11|4.02|W|display=inline,title}}\n| website       =\n| extra         = City of Philadelphia<br>Fairmount Park Commission             \n}}\n\n'''Lincoln Monument (Philadelphia)''' is a monument in [[Fairmount Park]], [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], United States. Designed by Neoclassical sculptor [[Randolph Rogers]] and completed in 1871,<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/> it was one of the first monuments erected to honor [[Abraham Lincoln|the assassinated president]].<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/> It is located in near the intersection of Kelly Drive and Sedgley Drive, opposite [[Boathouse Row]].<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Illustrated Souvenir of Fairmount Park, Philadelphia, Pa. (1918) (14771076592).jpg|thumb|left|Lincoln Monument, in 1918. Schuylkill River Drive (now Kelly Drive) passes left to right, Sedgley Drive recedes into the background right.]]\nPresident Lincoln was [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|assassinated on April 15, 1865]], and just over one month later the Lincoln Monument Association was formed in Philadelphia. Chaired by Mayor [[Alexander Henry (Philadelphia)|Alexander Henry]], the Association quickly raised $22,000 to commission a monument for the city honoring the late President of the United States.<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\">[https://www.associationforpublicart.org/artwork/abraham-lincoln/# Abraham Lincoln (1871)]\" (overview of the sculpture and its history). Philadelphia, Pennsylvania: Association for Public Art, retrieved online, July 12, 2019.</ref> A number of American sculptors were invited to submit a pair of models for the monument's sculpture&mdash;a single figure of Lincoln; and a group featuring Lincoln and an allegorical figure.<ref name=\"Savage\"/> [[Thomas Ball (artist)|Thomas Ball]] and Randolph Rogers were the only sculptors to submit the models.<ref name=\"Savage\"/> Instead of an allegorical figure, Rogers's group featured a crouching semi-nude enslaved woman, with a standing Lincoln helping her to rise.<ref name=\"Savage\">Kirk Savage, ''Standing Soldiers, Kneeling Slaves: Race, War and Monuments in Nineteenth-Century America'', (Princeton University Press, 1997), pp. 76-77, 83-84.</ref> Rogers was awarded the Philadelphia commission in 1866, but the Association chose his seated Lincoln over his slavery group.<ref name=\"Inquirer\">\"Our Martyr President: Tribute to His Memory: Unveiling of the Statue at the Park: Immense Outpouring of the People.\" Philadelphia, Pennsylvania: ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'', September 23, 1871.</ref>\n\nRogers, an American [[expatriate]] who trained and lived most of his life in Italy, created the [[Columbus Doors]] for the [[U.S. Capitol]], 1855-1861.<ref>[http://www.aoc.gov/cc/art/coldoors/index.cfm Columbus Doors,] Architect of the Capitol Webpage</ref>  Concurrently with the Philadelphia monument, he designed four major [[American Civil War|Civil War]] monuments&mdash;the [[Soldiers' National Monument]] (1865\u201369) at [[Gettysburg National Cemetery]]; the Rhode Island Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument (1866\u201371) in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]; the [[Michigan Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument]] (1867\u201372) in [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]]; and the [[Soldiers' Monument (Worcester, Massachusetts)|Soldiers' Monument]] (1871\u201374) in [[Worcester, Massachusetts]].\n \nRogers's final design was approved by the Association by March 1868:\n<blockquote>'''THE PHILADELPHIA LINCOLN MONUMENT.&mdash;'''<br>The Lincoln Monument Association of this city have adopted a design for a bronze statue of the late President of the United States, ABRAHAM LINCOLN. It is the work of RANDOLPH ROGERS, the American sculptor, at Rome. The figure is in a sitting posture, and will be nine feet high, and the pedestal, of granite, fourteen feet high. In the left hand Mr. LINCOLN holds the Emancipation Proclamation, and in his right the pen with which he has just signed it. The upper-side panels of the pedestal will be decorated with the arms of the United States on the one side and those of the City of Philadelphia on the other, in bronze, the corners being supported with Roman ''[[fasces]]'', also in bronze. on the lower corners of the pedestal are four American Eagles supporting festoons of laurels, all in bronze. The bronze work is to be executed at the Royal Foundry, at Munich. The whole cost of the monument will be about $30,000, of which the Association has some $25,000.<ref>''The Philadelphia Ledger'', March 3, 1868, p. 6.</ref></blockquote>\n\n''Lincoln the Emancipator'' was modeled by Rogers in [[Rome]].<ref name=\"Colimore\"/> The twice-life-size sculpture depicts a seated Lincoln in the act of signing the [[Emancipation Proclamation]],<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/> and is about {{cvt|8.67|ft|m|sortable=on}} in height.<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/>  Its stepped granite base is about {{cvt|17.75|ft|m|sortable=on}} in height,<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/> and features bronze garlands and eagles at the corners.<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/> The upper section of the base features four bronze plaques depicting a laurel wreath and crossed swords (east), medallions of liberty and justice (west), the Seal of Philadelphia (north), and the Great Seal of the United States (south).<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/> The statue and bronzework were cast in Germany at the Royal Foundry, [[Munich]] in 1870, at a cost of $3,000.<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/> The base was executed by Struthers & Company, a Philadelphia masonry firm.<ref name=\"SIRIS\">[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=158756K414C9B.61&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!21688~!6&ri=8&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Rogers&index=.AW&uindex=&oper=&term=Lincoln&index=.TW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=8 Lincoln (sculpture),] from SIRIS.</ref> \"The cost of the statue was nineteen thousand three hundred dollars, and of the granite base nine thousand four hundred dollars.\"<ref name=\"S&H\">John Thomas Scharf and Thompson Westcott, ''History of Philadelphia, 1609-1884, Volume 3'' (Philadelphia: L. H. Everts & Company, 1884), pp. 1859-1860.</ref> The monument's dedication is inscribed in granite on the front of the base. On the sides of the base are inscribed quotations from Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation, [[Gettysburg Address]], and [[Abraham Lincoln's second inaugural address|second inaugural address]].<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/>\n\n===Dedication===\n[[File:PH(1897) p32 PANORAMA FROM LEMON HILL OBSERVATORY, FAIRMOUNT PARK.jpg|thumb|The Lincoln Monument is visible at far left, below center, at the intersection of Schuylkill River Drive and Sedgley Drive.]]\nThe monument was installed on a grassy [[Roundabout|traffic circle]] at the intersection of Schuylkill River Drive (now Kelly Drive) and Sedgley Drive. It was dedicated on September 22, 1871. \"In the dedication ceremonies was included a parade of military, which embraced the [[118th Pennsylvania Infantry Regiment|First Division of Pennsylvania Volunteers, under Maj.-Gen. Charles M. Prevost]] and four brigades under [[Pennsylvania Army National Guard|Brig.-Gens. John P. Bankson]], [[William Hoffman (United States Army)|J. William Hoffman]], [[20th Pennsylvania Infantry Regiment|William B. Thomas]], and [[Louis Wagner (American general)|Louis Wagner]].\"<ref name=\"S&H\"/> The oratory address was delivered to a crowd of 50,000 by [[Morton McMichael#Family life|Col. William McMichael]],<ref name=\"Inquirer\"/> a former aide to Gen. [[Ulysses S. Grant]], who had been captured after the [[Battle of Shiloh]] and held in a Confederate prison.<ref name=\"JohnsonBrown1904\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=U-0UAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1849#v=onepage&q=McMichael&f=false \"William McMichael,\"] {{cite book|author1=Rossiter Johnson|author2=John Howard Brown|title=The Twentieth Century Biographical Dictionary of Notable Americans ...|url=|year=1904|publisher=Biographical Society|pages=1849}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, the monument was relocated about {{cvt|100|ft|m|sortable=on}} to the east side of Kelly Drive.<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Inscriptions==\nThe inscription on the pedestal reads:<br>\n(On plaque, front:)<br> \n<center>TO<br>\nABRAHAM LINCOLN<br>\nFROM A GRATEFUL PEOPLE</center><br>\n(On plaque, left side:)<br> \n<center>I DO ORDER AND DECLARE<br>\nTHAT ALL PERSONS HELD<br>\nAS SLAVES WITHIN THE STATES<br>\nIN REBELLION ARE AND HENCE-FORTH SHALL BE FREE</center><br>\n(On plaque, on back:)<br>\n<center>LET US HERE HIGHLY RESOLVE<br>\nTHAT THE GOVERNMENT OF THE PEOPLE<br>\nBY THE PEOPLE <br>\nAND FOR THE PEOPLE<br>\nSHALL NOT PERISH FROM THIS EARTH</center><br>\n(On plaque, on right:)<br>\n<center>WITH MALICE TOWARD NONE<br>\nWITH CHARITY TOWARD ALL<br>\nWITH FIRMNESS IN THE RIGHT<br>\nAS GOD GIVES US TO SEE THE RIGHT,<br>\nLET US FINISH THE WORK WE ARE IN<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/><br></center>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Philadelphia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Gasbarro, Norman. \"[http://civilwar.gratzpa.org/2012/10/abraham-lincoln-statue-in-fairmount-park-philadelphia/ Abraham Lincoln Statue in Fairmount Park, Philadelphia].\" Philadelphia, Pennsylvania: ''PA Historian'', October 4, 2012.\n*[http://www.philart.net/artist.php?id=197 Abraham Lincoln,] at Philadelphia Public Art\n\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1871 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Fairmount Park]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to Abraham Lincoln in the United States]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Statues in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Statues of Abraham Lincoln|Philadelphia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox monument\n| name          = Lincoln Monument\n| native_name   = \n| image         = Lincoln 1871 Fairmount.jpg\n| caption       = ''Lincoln the Emancipator''<ref name=\"Colimore\">Edward Colimore, ''The Philadelphia Inquirer's Guide to Historic Philadelphia'', (University Park, PA: Pennsylvania State University Press, 2003), p. 205.</ref>\n| location      = Kelly Drive & Sedgley Drive,<br>[[Fairmount Park]], Philadelphia\n| designer      = [[Randolph Rogers]]\n| type          = \n| material      = Sculpture: bronze<br>Base: granite & bronze\n| length        = \n| width         = \n| height        = Overall: {{cvt|26.5|ft|m|sortable=on}}<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/><br>Sculpture: {{cvt|8.67|ft|m|sortable=on}}\n| begin         = Commissioned 1866<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/><br>Cast 1870<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/>\n| complete      = \n| dedicated     =September 22, 1871<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/>\n| open          = \n| restore       = \n| dismantled    = \n| dedicated_to  = \n| map_name      = \n| map_text      = \n| map_width     = \n| map_relief    = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|39|58|10.56|N|75|11|4.02|W|display=inline,title}}\n| website       =\n| extra         = City of Philadelphia<br>Fairmount Park Commission             \n}}\n\n'''Lincoln Monument (Philadelphia)''' is a monument in [[Fairmount Park]], [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], United States. Designed by Neoclassical sculptor [[Randolph Rogers]] and completed in 1871,<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/> it was one of the first monuments erected to honor [[Abraham Lincoln|the assassinated president]].<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/> It is located in near the intersection of Kelly Drive and Sedgley Drive, opposite [[Boathouse Row]].<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Illustrated Souvenir of Fairmount Park, Philadelphia, Pa. (1918) (14771076592).jpg|thumb|left|Lincoln Monument, in 1918. Schuylkill River Drive (now Kelly Drive) passes left to right, Sedgley Drive recedes into the background right.]]\nPresident Lincoln was [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|assassinated on April 15, 1865]], and just over one month later the Lincoln Monument Association was formed in Philadelphia. Chaired by Mayor [[Alexander Henry (Philadelphia)|Alexander Henry]], the Association quickly raised $22,000 to commission a monument for the city honoring the late President of the United States.<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\">[https://www.associationforpublicart.org/artwork/abraham-lincoln/# Abraham Lincoln (1871)]\" (overview of the sculpture and its history). Philadelphia, Pennsylvania: Association for Public Art, retrieved online, July 12, 2019.</ref> A number of American sculptors were invited to submit a pair of models for the monument's sculpture&mdash;a single figure of Lincoln; and a group featuring Lincoln and an allegorical figure.<ref name=\"Savage\"/> [[Thomas Ball (artist)|Thomas Ball]] and Randolph Rogers were the only sculptors to submit the models.<ref name=\"Savage\"/> Instead of an allegorical figure, Rogers's group featured a crouching semi-nude enslaved woman, with a standing Lincoln helping her to rise.<ref name=\"Savage\">Kirk Savage, ''Standing Soldiers, Kneeling Slaves: Race, War and Monuments in Nineteenth-Century America'', (Princeton University Press, 1997), pp. 76-77, 83-84.</ref> Rogers was awarded the Philadelphia commission in 1866, but the Association chose his seated Lincoln over his slavery group.<ref name=\"Inquirer\">\"Our Martyr President: Tribute to His Memory: Unveiling of the Statue at the Park: Immense Outpouring of the People.\" Philadelphia, Pennsylvania: ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'', September 23, 1871.</ref>\n\nRogers, an American [[expatriate]] who trained and lived most of his life in Italy, created the [[Columbus Doors]] for the [[U.S. Capitol]], 1855-1861.<ref>[http://www.aoc.gov/cc/art/coldoors/index.cfm Columbus Doors,] Architect of the Capitol Webpage</ref>  Concurrently with the Philadelphia monument, he designed four major [[American Civil War|Civil War]] monuments&mdash;the [[Soldiers' National Monument]] (1865\u201369) at [[Gettysburg National Cemetery]]; the Rhode Island Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument (1866\u201371) in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]; the [[Michigan Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument]] (1867\u201372) in [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]]; and the [[Soldiers' Monument (Worcester, Massachusetts)|Soldiers' Monument]] (1871\u201374) in [[Worcester, Massachusetts]].\n \nRogers's final design was approved by the Association by March 1868:\n<blockquote>'''THE PHILADELPHIA LINCOLN MONUMENT.&mdash;'''<br>The Lincoln Monument Association of this city have adopted a design for a bronze statue of the late President of the United States, ABRAHAM LINCOLN. It is the work of RANDOLPH ROGERS, the American sculptor, at Rome. The figure is in a sitting posture, and will be nine feet high, and the pedestal, of granite, fourteen feet high. In the left hand Mr. LINCOLN holds the Emancipation Proclamation, and in his right the pen with which he has just signed it. The upper-side panels of the pedestal will be decorated with the arms of the United States on the one side and those of the City of Philadelphia on the other, in bronze, the corners being supported with Roman ''fasces'', also in bronze. on the lower corners of the pedestal are four American Eagles supporting festoons of laurels, all in bronze. The bronze work is to be executed at the Royal Foundry, at Munich. The whole cost of the monument will be about $30,000, of which the Association has some $25,000.<ref>''The Philadelphia Ledger'', March 3, 1868, p. 6.</ref></blockquote>\n\n''Lincoln the Emancipator'' was modeled by Rogers in [[Rome]].<ref name=\"Colimore\"/> The twice-life-size sculpture is about {{cvt|8.67|ft|m|sortable=on}} in height,<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/> and depicts a seated Lincoln in the act of signing the [[Emancipation Proclamation]].<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/> Its stepped granite base is about {{cvt|17.75|ft|m|sortable=on}} in height,<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/> and features bronze garlands and eagles at the corners.<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/> The upper section of the base features four bronze plaques depicting a laurel wreath and crossed swords (east), medallions of liberty and justice (west), the Seal of Philadelphia (north), and the Great Seal of the United States (south).<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/> The statue and bronzework were cast in Germany at the Royal Foundry, [[Munich]] in 1870, at a cost of $3,000.<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/> The base was executed by Struthers & Company, a Philadelphia masonry firm.<ref name=\"SIRIS\">[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=158756K414C9B.61&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!21688~!6&ri=8&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Rogers&index=.AW&uindex=&oper=&term=Lincoln&index=.TW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=8 Lincoln (sculpture),] from SIRIS.</ref> \"The cost of the statue was nineteen thousand three hundred dollars, and of the granite base nine thousand four hundred dollars.\"<ref name=\"S&H\">John Thomas Scharf and Thompson Westcott, ''History of Philadelphia, 1609-1884, Volume 3'' (Philadelphia: L. H. Everts & Company, 1884), pp. 1859-1860.</ref> The monument's dedication is inscribed in granite on the front of the base. On the sides of the base are inscribed quotations from Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation, [[Gettysburg Address]], and [[Abraham Lincoln's second inaugural address|second inaugural address]].<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/>\n\n===Dedication===\n[[File:PH(1897) p32 PANORAMA FROM LEMON HILL OBSERVATORY, FAIRMOUNT PARK.jpg|thumb|The Lincoln Monument is visible at far left, below center, at the intersection of Schuylkill River Drive and Sedgley Drive.]]\nThe monument was installed on a grassy [[Roundabout|traffic circle]] at the intersection of Schuylkill River Drive (now Kelly Drive) and Sedgley Drive. It was dedicated on September 22, 1871. \"In the dedication ceremonies was included a parade of military, which embraced the [[118th Pennsylvania Infantry Regiment|First Division of Pennsylvania Volunteers, under Maj.-Gen. Charles M. Prevost]] and four brigades under [[Pennsylvania Army National Guard|Brig.-Gens. John P. Bankson]], [[William Hoffman (United States Army)|J. William Hoffman]], [[20th Pennsylvania Infantry Regiment|William B. Thomas]], and [[Louis Wagner (American general)|Louis Wagner]].\"<ref name=\"S&H\"/> The oratory address was delivered to a crowd of 50,000 by [[Morton McMichael#Family life|Col. William McMichael]],<ref name=\"Inquirer\"/> a former aide to Gen. [[Ulysses S. Grant]], who had been captured after the [[Battle of Shiloh]] and held in a Confederate prison.<ref name=\"JohnsonBrown1904\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=U-0UAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1849#v=onepage&q=McMichael&f=false \"William McMichael,\"] {{cite book|author1=Rossiter Johnson|author2=John Howard Brown|title=The Twentieth Century Biographical Dictionary of Notable Americans ...|url=|year=1904|publisher=Biographical Society|pages=1849}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, the monument was relocated about {{cvt|100|ft|m|sortable=on}} to the east side of Kelly Drive.<ref name=\"associationforpublicart\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Inscriptions==\nThe inscription on the pedestal reads:<br>\n(On plaque, front:)<br> \n<center>TO<br>\nABRAHAM LINCOLN<br>\nFROM A GRATEFUL PEOPLE</center><br>\n(On plaque, left side:)<br> \n<center>I DO ORDER AND DECLARE<br>\nTHAT ALL PERSONS HELD<br>\nAS SLAVES WITHIN THE STATES<br>\nIN REBELLION ARE AND HENCE-FORTH SHALL BE FREE</center><br>\n(On plaque, on back:)<br>\n<center>LET US HERE HIGHLY RESOLVE<br>\nTHAT THE GOVERNMENT OF THE PEOPLE<br>\nBY THE PEOPLE <br>\nAND FOR THE PEOPLE<br>\nSHALL NOT PERISH FROM THIS EARTH</center><br>\n(On plaque, on right:)<br>\n<center>WITH MALICE TOWARD NONE<br>\nWITH CHARITY TOWARD ALL<br>\nWITH FIRMNESS IN THE RIGHT<br>\nAS GOD GIVES US TO SEE THE RIGHT,<br>\nLET US FINISH THE WORK WE ARE IN<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/><br></center>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Philadelphia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Gasbarro, Norman. \"[http://civilwar.gratzpa.org/2012/10/abraham-lincoln-statue-in-fairmount-park-philadelphia/ Abraham Lincoln Statue in Fairmount Park, Philadelphia].\" Philadelphia, Pennsylvania: ''PA Historian'', October 4, 2012.\n*[http://www.philart.net/artist.php?id=197 Abraham Lincoln,] at Philadelphia Public Art\n\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1871 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Fairmount Park]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to Abraham Lincoln in the United States]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Statues in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Statues of Abraham Lincoln|Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "BoringHistoryGuy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statue_of_Abraham_Lincoln_(Philadelphia)"}
